<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900529-0099</DOCNO><DOCID>900529-0099.</DOCID><HL>   McDonnell Douglas Says It   Fired 150 Workers in Scam</HL><DATE>05/29/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><CO>   MD</CO><LP>   LOS ANGELES -- McDonnell Douglas Corp. said it fired about150 employees that it alleges were involved in a scamstemming from a company program that allowed employees toborrow as much as $4,000 interest-free to buy personalcomputers.   The workers were ushered out of the aerospace concern'stransport aircraft division here after a two-month internalinvestigation disclosed they were misusing the loans,McDonnell Douglas said.</LP><TEXT>   &quot;People were submitting phony bills of sale,&quot; said acompany spokesman. Some employees got the invoices fromco-workers who then received a cash kickback from borrowers,the company said. The loans were supposed to be used topurchase computers compatible with the company's, soemployees could work at home or become more adept at usingthe computers.   The scheme was uncovered by corporate accountants inApril, the spokesman said, and the investigation iscontinuing. Eventually, as many as 200 employees may be firedfor participating in the scheme, McDonnell Douglas said.   The company doesn't know how much money it may have lostas a result of the alleged fraud, said the spokesman, but itwill seek restitution. The company hasn't filed a complaintwith the District Attorney's office, he said.   McDonnell Douglas has canceled the program, in which morethan 5,000 employees have taken out the interest-free loanssince the program began in 1984.</TEXT></DOC>